# Valheim Mod Debugging Rule

After every iteration when debugging Valheim mod code:

## 1. Check the Log Output

Read the last 30 lines of the BepInEx log:
```bash
tail -30 ~/.config/r2modmanPlus-local/Valheim/profiles/valheim-modding/BepInEx/LogOutput.log
```

Look for:
- Our plugin's log messages (prefixed with `[Valheim Villages]`)
- Unity errors or warnings
- Harmony patching issues
- Null reference exceptions

## 2. Check the build for compilation errors

```bash
dotnet build # from the directory containing the csproj
```

Look for:
- CS1061 which indicates the definition does not exist.  This typically happens when the agent hallucinates an attribute instead of locating it in Unity's object hierarchy.
- Missing assemblies for unity, valheim, or bepinex

The agent should always ensure that the build compiles without errors, or ask the user for guidance if the documentation is insufficient to resolve it.

## 3. Verify API Access with monodis

Before accessing any Valheim field or method, verify it exists and is accessible using `monodis`:

```bash
# Dump full disassembly (one-time, reuse across session)
VALHEIM_DLL="$HOME/.local/share/Steam/steamapps/common/Valheim/valheim_Data/Managed/assembly_valheim.dll"
monodis "$VALHEIM_DLL" > /tmp/valheim.il

# Find all fields/methods containing a keyword
grep -i "yourKeyword" /tmp/valheim.il | head -30

# List all fields in a specific class
grep -A 500 "\.class.*ClassName" /tmp/valheim.il | grep "\.field" | head -50

# Find method signatures
grep -A 200 "\.class.*ClassName" /tmp/valheim.il | grep "\.method" | head -30
```

### Access Modifiers in IL

When inspecting IL output, these access modifiers indicate what code can access the member:

- `public` - accessible from anywhere
- `family` - protected (subclasses only)
- `private` - only within the declaring class
- `assembly` - internal (same assembly only)

### Alternative: Publicized Assemblies

For better IDE IntelliSense during development, consider using [BepInEx.AssemblyPublicizer](https://github.com/BepInEx/BepInEx.AssemblyPublicizer) to create versions of Valheim assemblies where all private members become public.

## 4. Reference Azumatt's ItemManager

If the issue involves item/prefab registration, check Azumatt's battle-tested implementation:
https://github.com/AzumattDev/ItemManagerModTemplate/blob/master/ItemManager.cs

Key patterns to look for:
- How prefabs are registered with ObjectDB
- How ZNetScene prefabs are added
- The `UpdateRegisters()` call after adding items
- Patch priorities and ordering

## 5. Consult Documentation

### Unity Documentation
https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Component.html

Useful for:
- MonoBehaviour lifecycle (Awake, Start, OnEnable)
- GameObject instantiation and prefab handling
- Component access patterns

### Valheim Modding Wiki
https://github.com/Valheim-Modding/Wiki/wiki/Item-Variants#inventory

Useful for:
- Item variant system
- Valheim-specific component requirements
- ObjectDB and ZNetScene integration patterns

## 6. Common Issues Checklist

- [ ] Is the prefab added to both ObjectDB.m_items AND the hash map?
- [ ] Is the prefab added to ZNetScene.m_prefabs AND m_namedPrefabs?
- [ ] Was `ObjectDB.UpdateRegisters()` called after adding items?
- [ ] Is the ZNetView component properly configured with the correct prefab hash?
- [ ] Are Harmony patches running at the right priority?
